A HERO <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pilot_in_command" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pilot_in_command" target="_blank">airline captain</a> saved his <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Passenger" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Passenger" target="_blank">passengers</a> with just seven seconds to spare after the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Autopilot" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Autopilot" target="_blank">autopilot</a> tried to <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Crash_%28computing%29" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Crash_%28computing%29" target="_blank">crash</a> his <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Aircraft" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Aircraft" target="_blank">aircraft</a> into the seaPassengers on the islandhopping Saab 2000 <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Satellite" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Satellite" target="_blank">sat</a> in <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Terrorism" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Terrorism" target="_blank">terror</a> as the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Boeing_757" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Boeing_757" target="_blank">plane</a> ignored the crew's commands to climb  and instead sent itself into a nosediveThe <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Boeing_757" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Boeing_757" target="_blank">plane</a> which had been struck by lightning fell to just 1100 ft before its <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pilot_in_command" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pilot_in_command" target="_blank">captain</a> wrestled back control and applied full powerThe drama occurred on December 14 as the Loganair <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Flight_Lieutenant" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Flight_Lieutenant" target="_blank">flight</a> from Aberdeen approached its destination at Sumburgh airport Shetland at nightThe weather was so bad  thunderstorms with rain snow hail and 70mph winds  the crew broke off their approach when they were still seven miles awayMoments later a ball of lightning appeared in the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Cockpit" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Cockpit" target="_blank">cockpit</a> and a bolt struck the nose travelling the full length of the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Boeing_757" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Boeing_757" target="_blank">plane</a> before leaving at the tailAs the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/First_Officer_%28civil_aviation%29" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/First_Officer_%28civil_aviation%29" target="_blank">copilot</a> declared a <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Mayday_%28distress_signal%29" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Mayday_%28distress_signal%29" target="_blank">mayday</a> the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Aviator" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Aviator" target="_blank">pilot</a> tried to gain height  but every move was countered by the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Autopilot" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Autopilot" target="_blank">autopilot</a> The more aggressive his movements on the control column the less effect it seemed to have When it reached 4000ft the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Boeing_757" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Boeing_757" target="_blank">plane</a> suddenly pitched nose down and started falling out of the sky at 9500ft a minute  giving the crew barely 20 <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Second" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Second" target="_blank">seconds</a> to act before crashing into the icy North SeaAt 1100ft as âPull up' alarms sounded in the cabin the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pilot_in_command" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pilot_in_command" target="_blank">captain</a> applied full power and the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Aircraft" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Aircraft" target="_blank">aircraft</a> finally started to climb The <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Boeing_757" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Boeing_757" target="_blank">plane</a> diverted to Aberdeen where it landed <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Safety" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Safety" target="_blank">safely</a> and shaken <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Passenger" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Passenger" target="_blank">passengers</a> disembarkedA report into the neardisaster by the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Air_Accidents_Investigation_Branch" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Air_Accidents_Investigation_Branch" target="_blank">Air Accident Investigation Branch</a> said the crew may have thought the lighting strike had disabled the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Autopilot" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Autopilot" target="_blank">autopilot</a> because it had knocked out some of the other controlsIn fact it was still operating and trying to adjust and fly at the level it has been instructed Only when the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Computer" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Computer" target="_blank">computers</a> became overloaded with faulty <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Data" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Data" target="_blank">data</a> during the plunge did it disengage itself and give the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Aviator" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Aviator" target="_blank">pilot</a> <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Second" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Second" target="_blank">seconds</a> to save the flightThe <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Air_Accidents_Investigation_Branch" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Air_Accidents_Investigation_Branch" target="_blank">AAIB</a> report said âAlthough the pilots' actions suggested that they were under the impression the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Autopilot" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Autopilot" target="_blank">autopilot</a> had disengaged at the moment of the lightning strike recorded <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Data" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Data" target="_blank">data</a> showed that it had remained engagedâThe pilots' noseup <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Flight_dynamics" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Flight_dynamics" target="_blank">pitch</a> inputs were countered by the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Autopilot" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Autopilot" target="_blank">autopilot</a> <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Flight_dynamics" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Flight_dynamics" target="_blank">pitch</a> trim function which made a prolonged nosedown <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Flight_dynamics" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Flight_dynamics" target="_blank">pitch</a> trim input in an attempt to maintain its <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Altitude" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Altitude" target="_blank">altitude</a> tracking function until it disengaged This accounted for the perception that the control response was not normalâIt added âAs the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Aircraft" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Aircraft" target="_blank">aircraft</a> reached 4000ft the pitch attitude tended towards nosedown and a descent began Invalid <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Data" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Data" target="_blank">data</a> from one of the air data computers then caused the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Autopilot" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Autopilot" target="_blank">autopilot</a> to disengage The <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Flight_dynamics" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Flight_dynamics" target="_blank">pitch</a> trim was by this time almost fully nosedown and the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Aircraft" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Aircraft" target="_blank">aircraft</a> continued to <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Flight_dynamics" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Flight_dynamics" target="_blank">pitch</a> nosedown and descendâThe peak rate of descent was 9500 feet per minuteâThe report says no technical problems were fund with the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Boeing_757" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Boeing_757" target="_blank">plane</a> which is now back in service and pilot training now included simulations of this incidentThe <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Air_Accidents_Investigation_Branch" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Air_Accidents_Investigation_Branch" target="_blank">AAIB</a> probe is also continuing looking at crew training <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Autopilot" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Autopilot" target="_blank">autopilot</a> design and any âhuman factors' Try your hand at our news quiz 
